```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
    % Axes
    \draw[->] (-2,0) -- (2,0) node[below] {$\Re$};
    \draw[->] (0,-1.5) -- (0,1.5) node[left] {$\Im$};

    % Contour
    \draw[thick, decoration={markings, mark=at position 0.25 with {\arrow{>}}, 
                               mark=at position 0.75 with {\arrow{>}}},
          postaction={decorate}] 
          (1,0) node[below right] {$\kappa^2$} 
          arc (0:90:1) 
          -- (-0.2,1) 
          arc (90:180:0.2) 
          -- (-1,0) 
          arc (180:270:0.5) 
          -- (0.2,-0.5) 
          arc (-90:0:0.5);

    % Dashed line and sigma(T)
    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway, below] {$\sigma(T)$};

    % Labels
    \node at (-1.2,0) {$-\lambda/2$};
    \node at (1,1) {$\Gamma_\lambda$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- The `\draw[->]` commands create the coordinate axes, with labels for the real ($\Re$) and imaginary ($\Im$) parts.
- The contour $\Gamma_\lambda$ is drawn using a combination of `arc` and line segments (`--`). The `decoration.markings` library is used to place arrowheads at specified positions along the contour.
- The dashed line representing $\sigma(T)$ is drawn from the origin to the point $\kappa^2$ on the real axis.
- Labels for $-\lambda/2$, $\kappa^2$, and $\Gamma_\lambda$ are added to complete the diagram.

This code ensures that the visual representation matches the original image closely.

